ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, the nitrogen-sulfur co-doped CDs (N, S-CDs) were generated by using o-phenylenediamine and 2,2′-dithiobenzoic acid to integrate fluorescence and colorimetric detection for cobalt ions in actual aquatic environments. The basic principle of this detection strategy involves the oxidation of Co (II) to Co(III) by the pyrrole nitrogen and SO3
                     2- present on the surface of N, S-CDs, resulting in the formation of a non-luminous metal complex and inducing a static quenching effect (SQE). Notably, the electrostatic interaction between the positively charged metal complexes and the negatively charged surface of N, S-CDs promotes the agglomeration of the metal complexes, thereby achieving effective visual screening (Scheme 1
                     ). This capability holds the potential to facilitate the development of simple analytical instruments for metal ion detection.

The performance of N, S-CDs for the detection of Co(II) in actual aquatic environments was explored. Electroplating wastewater and lake water were almost free of Co(II) after simple pretreatment, and then the standard concentration of Co(II) was added for monitoring purposes. The recovery rate ranged from 94 % to 103 % (Table 1
                        ), representing the high accuracy and good recovery of the fluorescence and colorimetric dual-mode approach. In addition, a recovery experiment was performed using a flame atomic absorption spectrometer (AAS-6300C) (FIG. S10). The recovery rate ranged from 94 % to 106 % in Table 1
                        . The stringent pretreatment procedure and high precision devices generate instabilities in the determination of low levels of Co(II) recovery. Compared with AAS, the dual-mode approach has advantages in simple preprocessing, high stability and high sensitivity to some extent.
